    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-04-02T07:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-04-02T07:30:00-05:00" n="357"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d357">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">411.56D31/4–251: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Indonesia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cochran</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Djakarta</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-04-02T20:00:00+07:30"
                            >April 2, 1951—8 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1353. Rubber contract negotiations commenced this morning in conversations
                    between Sumitro,<note n="1" xml:id="d357fn1">Dr. Sumitro Djojohadikusumo,
                        Minister of Trade and Industry and a member of the <gloss target="#t_PSI1"
                            >PSI</gloss>.</note> Zain, Darmawan,<note n="2" xml:id="d357fn2">Dr.
                        Darmawan, Director-General of the Ministry of Trade and Industry.</note>
                        Osmaoen,<note n="3" xml:id="d357fn3">Member of the Ministry of Trade and
                        Industry.</note> Wilson, Coerr and MacFadyen.<note n="4" xml:id="d357fn4">An
                        employee of <gloss target="#t_GSA1">GSA</gloss> and a member of the rubber
                        purchasing mission.</note> After <gloss target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss>s had
                    given usual parade of difficulties inherent for them in meeting US desires,
                    cordial atmosphere was established and agreement reached that conversations wld
                    be pursued on basis (1) US wld offer commitment that US Govt wld extend good
                    offices to satisfy basic <gloss target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss> civilian needs
                    mfg goods (in accordance note authorized <gloss target="#t_Deptel1"
                        >Deptel</gloss> 1042, Mar 27). (2) Quantity price and other details of
                    specific purchase contract wld be worked out mutually. (3) <gloss
                        target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss>s wld also study possible methods whereby
                        <gloss target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss> Govt cld implement govt to govt
                    contract.</p>
                <p>Meeting this afternoon with Darmawan, Zain, Osmaoen and two Dutch technicians
                    reached no conclusions. <gloss target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss>s were given
                    informal draft US note as mentioned above and were asked to consider as starting
                    point a contract to provide 200,000 tons in 18 months at 48 cents per pound.
                    They spent whole session, however, reiterating general arguments which they had
                    advanced at London.<note n="5" xml:id="d357fn5">The reference is to the London
                        Rubber Conference.</note> Discussions to be resumed tomorrow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cochran</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
